23:26.940 --> 23:29.640
far, weren't you? And actually, the biggest 
reason they wanted to get rid of him is because he

23:34.300 --> 23:36.420
had served twenty-three years. And I mean, they 
were really on me to, you get to a point where

23:43.860 --> 23:46.240
regardless of what you did, they're still going to 
be after you, and I had told them I was going to

23:46.220 --> 23:51.260
retire in August of eighty-seven, and they were 
having a good time. They were having some awards

23:53.710 --> 23:55.590
meeting up there, and Erdman, and Fletcher, and 
I've forgotten who else called me in the office. I

24:04.350 --> 24:06.630
remember one, they had gotten an award, and I'd 
been at the award meeting, and they called me in the

24:06.610 --> 24:08.610
office, and they were saying, they said, well, 
Charlie, why don't you just step down right now,

24:12.470 --> 24:14.930
and we can start hunting, I mean, not right now, but 
step down here in a month or two, and then we can

24:17.010 --> 24:19.150
start looking for a new department head. I said, 
well, I told you I was going to step down in August.

24:21.450 --> 24:22.311
What's wrong with that? Well, we could just do so 
much better if you just, you know, step down, and I

24:24.650 --> 24:28.370
said, well, I don't care to until the time 
allocated, and so they got Richardson in there,

24:33.880 --> 24:37.110
and they went at it again. I said, when Richardson, 
I said, if you want me to step down so damn bad, I'll

24:40.330 --> 24:42.610
quit this minute. Do you want it? And that was the 
end of it. They didn't want it that fast, and so I

24:46.350 --> 24:51.890
had, I served on until exactly when I told them I'd, 
I was ready to step down. All right, let's go back to

24:56.510 --> 24:58.970
Mr. Rutter. Mr. Rutter dies in early 1970. Yeah, I 
had arranged for him to give a paper over in, I

25:06.150 --> 25:10.340
believe it was Atlanta, and I had written it on 
continuing education, and I went in to see him, and

25:10.320 --> 25:14.700
he, I believe it was really dragging on him, 
because he said, Charlie, I just don't see how I can

25:17.520 --> 25:19.400
do this. I said, sure, you can do it. All you got to do 
is read it. I'll write the dang thing. All you got to

25:23.020 --> 25:24.561
do is read it. And Morgan was, used to be here as 
president, was the one that was, had asked me to

25:28.220 --> 25:31.680
give him, get something, get him to give a paper. 
And so it turned out that Fred Benson had to read it.

25:37.660 --> 25:41.420
He had the stroke before that occurred. So I'd just 
been over to his office a little before that. All

25:44.520 --> 25:48.220
right, then we briefly had Clyde Freeman, I 
believe it is, as the interim, and then Jack

25:48.200 --> 25:51.120
Williams. Let's see, no, we had Ludeke. Oh, I'm 
sorry. General Ludeke. General Ludeke, yes, yes.

25:58.560 --> 26:01.720
Did Ludeke have any, did you have any interaction 
with him? Oh, yeah. He asked me to look into this

26:02.288 --> 26:04.800
faculty club. And I looked all over the place and 
found out that unless you had drinks, if you wanted

26:08.500 --> 26:12.440
one to make profit, you're going to have to have 
something like that. And another thing that I

26:12.420 --> 26:16.180
asked him to do, and it was already too late, I said 
the way that thing is designed over there, you

26:16.160 --> 26:20.780
can't have a meeting in it. And it needs to be to 
where you can have all the people in there and have

26:24.060 --> 26:30.720
something in the faculty club that's a dinner of 
some sort where you have a speaker. And that way,

26:30.700 --> 26:34.200
you can, it can make money that way. And he said, 
well, it's too late to change it. And he wanted me

26:36.980 --> 26:42.780
to, and I did, and I finally just reported to him 
that I didn't think, that they could not make a go of

26:42.760 --> 26:49.080
it unless they had some, and they, it's, I've been 
proven correct. Right. I was a junior member of

26:51.060 --> 26:52.081
that. Oh. Yeah. I was a junior member of that 
committee for that, all of that expansion of the

26:54.060 --> 26:58.240
MSC and the Rudder Tower. And I was arguing the same 
thing as you because the faculty club on the 11th

27:00.000 --> 27:09.100
and 12th floors, each of those little dining areas 
is so small that you can't get enough people in one

27:09.080 --> 27:16.000
place. And so I told them that, and it wasn't. But 
the architect is? Somebody saw it, one in Dallas,

27:20.760 --> 27:23.920
like that, and I think I've eaten in that one in 
Dallas. And that's the way they wanted it

27:23.900 --> 27:29.160
designed, that's the reason it got designed that 
way. And Rudder, and Ludeke said, well, it's just

27:29.140 --> 27:33.340
too late, you know, to change it. And he accepted 
it. He just didn't like it much, but he, I just told

27:34.320 --> 27:40.080
him, you know, we just can't, it's hard enough to 
get people to go out at night and eat anyway. What

27:44.060 --> 27:50.200
would you, what description would you give of the 
manner in which he filled in as the interim

27:50.180 --> 27:51.201
president?

27:54.180 --> 27:58.740
I think General Ludeke was one of the top people 
that, and actually Fred told me that General

27:58.720 --> 28:02.340
Rudder got him, just hired him. And Fred said, I 
tried to get him to take Ludeke and let him help him

28:02.320 --> 28:08.120
administer, and he wouldn't do it. He wanted to do 
it all himself. And so he gave him to me. But he ran

28:12.690 --> 28:15.590
the station, I worked for him some of them there. 
But he was really a nice individual. Describe his.

28:23.930 --> 28:24.380
Very. Very low key, but very definite. I sat with 
him on committee meetings, and he didn't throw his

28:28.340 --> 28:33.520
former rank or anything around. And in fact, I was 
just over interviewing the transportation

28:35.110 --> 28:40.040
department. His son is named Al Ludeke, and he's 
head of all planning over there. And I didn't know

28:44.120 --> 28:46.740
about it until I called over there. The same Al 
Ludeke, he went to A&M, but his son, Al Ludeke's son

28:46.720 --> 28:54.240
is also named Al Ludeke, and he's running the 
planning division of the Texas Transportation

28:54.220 --> 29:02.570
Department, TxDOT. And I went over and we had an 
interview with him. The few times I was in his

29:04.430 --> 29:13.650
office, I never saw a more orderly, cleaner desk. 
Everything seemed to be in order. And with me, he

29:17.230 --> 29:23.260
asked very few questions. Mm-hm. He was always 
very skillfully planned, and he seemed to be an

29:23.964 --> 29:29.980
extremely good listener. Mm-hm. Well, you see, 
what happened was that after the war, the Atomic

29:30.764 --> 29:38.200
Energy Commission, they put him in. He was running 
that, but you never heard of him. He wasn't out

29:41.040 --> 29:44.400
there making a lot of racket. Then they had trouble 
with that space laboratory out in Stanford. And so

29:51.040 --> 29:54.200
they sent him out there, and they had been screwing 
up. When he got out there, they started working.

29:55.940 --> 29:56.586
Yep. And so everywhere he went, he was able to solve 
the problems, and he didn't make a big stir about

30:00.500 --> 30:01.521
it. So I like, he was a chemical engineering 
graduate, class of 1932. Now he came back after

30:06.340 --> 30:11.660
serving as interim president, he came back to 
engineering. Is that right? Yeah, no. He was

30:13.632 --> 30:15.920
serving in engineering before he ever became. 
Well, but I mean, he went over to the president,

30:15.900 --> 30:18.920
then? Well, I'm not really sure he ever really 
served any over there. I think that was just a

30:21.900 --> 30:22.921
discussion before. Oh, okay. And then whenever, 
when Rutter died, they took him out of engineering

30:24.668 --> 30:31.880
and made him acting president. All right, but then 
after Williams came, he came back over to? He may

30:36.400 --> 30:37.421
have. I don't really remember. Jack Williams 
came. Describe your impressions of Jack Williams

30:42.120 --> 30:44.980
as president. Well, I think he was the man for that 
time.

30:52.160 --> 30:53.441
I'm not really sure that I. . . You don't have a 
chance to say that you'd rank him anywhere. Oh, I

30:55.990 --> 30:58.850
think he was one of the, I don't know, that I'd rank 
him anywhere near Rutter. I think Rutter is one of

30:58.830 --> 31:03.490
the best ones that had ever been here, but yep, I 
would have given him the poorest chances when he

31:03.470 --> 31:08.090
came, of anybody we've ever had. But I think Jack 
did a good job as president, and because of his

31:08.070 --> 31:16.310
academic background, he could see what was 
needed. I think anything he did to get . . . Then what

31:19.730 --> 31:20.751
did you think Jack did? I think he did a slope. I 
think he did a slope. I think he did a slope.

